ial meanings of gender, sexuality and medicine, historians have considered the movements of travellers, migrants, military bodies and medical personnel, and ‘transnational lives’. This book examines an empire-wide discourse of ‘madness’ as part of this inquiry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImmigrantsxPsychologyxAustralia. 0aImmigrantsxPsychologyxNew Zealand. 0aImmigrantszAustraliaxPsychology. 0aImmigrantszNew ZealandxPsychology. 0aPeople with mental disabilitiesxInstitutional carexHistoryx19th centuryxAustralia. 0aPeople with mental disabilitiesxInstitutional carexHistoryx19th centuryxNew Zealand. 0aPeople with mental disabilitiesxInstitutional carezAustraliaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPeople with mental disabilitiesxInstitutional carezNew ZealandxHistoryy19th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAustralasia.  aInsanity.  acolonial.  aidentity.  aimmigrants.  ainstitutions.  amadness.  amigration.  amobility.1 aColeborne, Catharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499671040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784996710423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784996710/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles